### Executive build note

Anderson County is a strong next county Focus Mode because it supports a public-safe governance-and-place proof slice without depending on sensitive exact locations. The first version should stay small: county/city official web anchors, Garnett civic context, public offices and public service categories, county-level working-landscape aggregates, public recreation candidates only after official source verification, and historical orientation only when supported by authoritative sources.

The strongest Anderson-specific boundary is the public-convenience/legal-reliance problem. The Anderson County official site exposes county departments, public safety, property services, and public-facing information, but it also states that web information is for public convenience and that legal reliance should go to official records. KFM must preserve that distinction. Focus Mode may help users understand what kind of public source exists, what it can support, and where to go for official authority. It must not infer title, ownership, access rights, zoning status, legal obligations, emergency action, live road/trail/facility safety, or infrastructure vulnerability from public web visibility.

